   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "5b98a9dc-849d-467b-8faa-6af6a9094051",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Aggregators - Lecture"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "9f3a6eb0-3197-482e-b524-6a246e73f246",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Aggregators\n",
    "\n",
    "Function that iterates through every value in an iterable and returns a single value that usually takes into account every element of that iterable\n",
    "\n",
    "min(iterable) -> minimum value in the iterable\n",
    "max(iterable) -> maximum value in the iterable\n",
    "sum(iterable) -> sum of all values in the iterable"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "1343f310-08b2-4de9-98f9-a519f3723d46",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Associated Truth Values\n",
    "\n",
    "You should already know this but let's review:\n",
    "Every object in Python has an associated truth value\n",
    "bool(obj) -> True/False\n",
    "\n",
    "Every object has a True truth value except:\n",
    "- None\n",
    "- False\n",
    "- 0 in any numeric type (e.g. 0, 0.0, 0+0j, ..)\n",
    "- empty sequences (e.g. list, tuple, string, ..)\n",
    "- empty mapping types (e.g. dictionary, set, ..)\n",
    "- custom classes that implement a __bool__ or __len__ method that returns False or 0\n",
    "which have a False value"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "9dc07ec3-04a2-4839-b723-801993f54e50",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The any and all functions\n",
    "\n",
    "any(iterable) -> returns True if any (one or more) element in iterable is truthy, false otherwise\n",
    "all(iterable) -> returns True if all elements in iterable are truthy, false otherwise"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "c91b3e37-c929-4042-85c9-cf5fd3da2137",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Leveraging the any and all functions\n",
    "\n",
    "Often we are not interested in direct truth values of elements in our iterables\n",
    "-> want to know if any or all satisfy some condition -> if condition is True\n",
    "\n",
    "A function that takes a single argument and returns True or False is called a predicate\n",
    "We can make any and all more useful by first applying a predicate to each element of the iterable"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "8a0ec07c-c9c5-4a4a-a4e4-38a5fe793b1b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Example:\n",
    "\n",
    "Suppose we have some iterable\n",
    "l = [1, 2, 3, 4, 100]\n",
    "\n",
    "Want to know if every element is less than 10\n",
    "First define a suitable predicate\n",
    "pred = lambda x: x < 10\n",
    "Apply this predicate to every element of the iterable\n",
    "\n",
    "results = [pred(1), pred(2), pred(3), pred(4), pred(100)]\n",
    "        -> [True, True, True, True, False]\n",
    "\n",
    "Then we use all on these results \n",
    "all(results) -> False"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "451fce19-85b9-4b3e-b2e0-fcc8c3217e23",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "How do we apoply that predicate?\n",
    "\n",
    "The map function\n",
    "map(fn, iterable) -> applies fn to every element in iterable\n",
    "\n",
    "Comprehension\n",
    "(fn(item) for item in iterable)\n",
    "\n",
    "Or even:\n",
    "new_list = []\n",
    "for item in iterable:\n",
    "    new_list.append(fn(item))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
